						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/The-production-and-price-impact-of-biotechnology-crops" title="The production and price impact of biotechnology crops" alt="link">The production and price impact of biotechnology crops</a></h2>

	
					<p>By Graham Brookes, Tun-Hsiang Yu, Simla Tokgoz, and Amani Elobeid, January 2010. The working paper The Production and Price Impact of Biotech Crops, discuss about the production effects of the technology and impacts on cereal and oilseed markets through the use of agricultural commodity models. It analyzes the impacts on global production, consumption, trade and prices in the soybean, canola and corn sectors. The effect of no longer using the current widely used biotech traits in the corn, soybean and canola sectors would probably impact negatively on both the global supply and utilization of these crops, their derivatives and related markets for grain and oilseeds.</p>
							<p><span class="date">1/03/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/The-production-and-price-impact-of-biotechnology-crops">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Delivering-genetically-engineered-crops-to-poor-farmers-Recommendations-for-improved-biosafety-regulations-in-developing-countries" title="Delivering genetically engineered crops to poor farmers: Recommendations for improved biosafety regulations in developing countries" alt="link">Delivering genetically engineered crops to poor farmers: Recommendations for improved biosafety regulations in developing countries</a></h2>

	
					<p>By Falck-Zepeda, José, Cavalieri, Anthony and Zambrano, Patricia, International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI), 2009. Small-scale, resource-poor farmers in developing countries face daily stresses, including poor soils, drought, and lack of inputs. Ongoing trends such as climate change and population growth will likely exacerbate binding stresses. A new generation of genetically engineered (GE) crop research aims to alleviate these pressures through the improvement of subsistence crops—such as cassava, sorghum, and millet—that incorporate traits such as tolerance to drought, water, and aluminium in soils as well as plants with more efficient nitrogen and phosphor use. However, many developing countries lack the necessary biosafety systems for a timely and cost-effective adoption. This brief focuses on the regulatory reforms necessary for farmers and consumers in developing countries to benefit from GE crops.</p>
							<p><span class="date">1/03/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Delivering-genetically-engineered-crops-to-poor-farmers-Recommendations-for-improved-biosafety-regulations-in-developing-countries">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Undying-promise-Agricultural-biotechnology-s-pro-poor-narrative-ten-years-on" title="Undying promise: Agricultural biotechnology’s pro-poor narrative, ten years on" alt="link">Undying promise: Agricultural biotechnology’s pro-poor narrative, ten years on</a></h2>

	
					<p>By Dominic Glover, STEPS Working Paper 15, Brighton: STEPS Centre, 2009. Many people and organisations have sought to promote genetically modified (GM, transgenic) crops as a ‘pro-poor’ technology. However, developing-country farmers’ experiences with GM crops have been mixed. Some farmers have certainly benefited, but others have not. Predictably, the performance and impacts of transgenic crops depend critically on a range of technical, socio-economic and institutional factors. By themselves, genetically modified seeds are not enough to guarantee a good harvest or to create a sustainable and productive farm livelihood.</p>
							<p><span class="date">1/03/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Undying-promise-Agricultural-biotechnology-s-pro-poor-narrative-ten-years-on">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Pro-poor-biotechnology-and-biosafety-research-in-partnership-with-developing-countries" title="Pro-poor biotechnology and biosafety research in partnership with developing countries " alt="link">Pro-poor biotechnology and biosafety research in partnership with developing countries </a></h2>

	
					<p>By IFPRI, 2009. The majority of poor people in developing countries rely on agriculture for their food and livelihoods. However, they are increasingly vulnerable and food insecure due to declining agricultural productivity growth, climate change susceptibility, and volatile food and energy prices. As part of its commitment to improving livelihoods and reducing poverty, IFPRI is undertaking substantial work on food- and nutrition-related science and technology policy, with an emphasis on innovations that are relevant, safe, and accessible to poor people. Assessing the socioeconomic opportunities and risks of agricultural biotechnology for smallholder farming systems, poor consumers, biodiversity, and trade is a priority on IFPRI’s research agenda. IFPRI’s biotechnology research is also complemented by its work on biosafety policy issues.</p>
							<p><span class="date">4/02/2010</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Pro-poor-biotechnology-and-biosafety-research-in-partnership-with-developing-countries">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Learning-from-the-past-Successes-and-failures-with-agricultural-biotechnologies-in-developing-countries-over-the-last-20-years" title="“Learning from the past: Successes and failures with agricultural biotechnologies in developing countries over the last 20 years” " alt="link">“Learning from the past: Successes and failures with agricultural biotechnologies in developing countries over the last 20 years” </a></h2>

	
					<p>By FAO, June 2009. The biggest part of this 16-page document provides an overview of the main kinds of agricultural biotechnologies that have been used in the crop, forestry, livestock, fishery and agro-industry sectors in developing countries in the past and that were covered in a e-mail conference which runned from 8 June to 5 July 2009. It was hosted by the FAO Biotechnology Forum and was being held as part of the build up to the <a href="http://www.fao.org/biotech/abdc/conference-home/en/" target="_blank">FAO international technical conference on Agricultural Biotechnologies in Developing Countries</a>. </p>
							<p><span class="date">5/08/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Learning-from-the-past-Successes-and-failures-with-agricultural-biotechnologies-in-developing-countries-over-the-last-20-years">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Freedom-to-Innovate-Biotechnology-in-Africa-s-Development" title="Freedom to Innovate - Biotechnology in Africa’s Development" alt="document">Freedom to Innovate - Biotechnology in Africa’s Development</a></h2>

	
	
	
	
					<p>This report is about the role of biotechnology in the transformation of African economies. The implications of its recommendations, however, need to be seen beyond the confines of biological innovations. They address critical issues related to Africa’s place in a globalizing economy.</p>
							<p><span class="date">23/07/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="document" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Freedom-to-Innovate-Biotechnology-in-Africa-s-Development">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Biosafety-at-the-crossroads-An-analysis-of-South-Africa-s-marketing-and-trade-policies-for-genetically-modified-products" title="Biosafety at the crossroads: An analysis of South Africa’s marketing and trade policies for genetically modified products" alt="link">Biosafety at the crossroads: An analysis of South Africa’s marketing and trade policies for genetically modified products</a></h2>

	
					<p>By Guillaume P. Gruère, Debdatta Sengupta, IFPRI Discussion Paper, 2008. This paper analyses the marketing and trade policies for GM products in South Africa that have been successful in the past and critically reviews recent reforms to these policies. By providing trade volume estimates of potentially GM products, this paper shows that South Africa is effectively a significant exporter and importer of both GM and non GM products. The past 10 years have demonstrated that South Africa’s success in taking advantage of biotechnologies under changing global conditions stems mainly from its adaptation capacity and the flexibility of its system. Based on the analysis presented in this paper, six policy recommendations are provided to improve rather than rigidify market and trade regulations - policies that would allow South Africa to better adapt to global changes, to manage risks rigorously but efficiently, and to take advantage of safe and potentially promising new GM technologies.</p>
							<p><span class="date">11/05/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Biosafety-at-the-crossroads-An-analysis-of-South-Africa-s-marketing-and-trade-policies-for-genetically-modified-products">Read more...</a>
</div>
<br class="cl">
</div>
</p>
						
						<p><div class="item">
<h2><a class="listing" style="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Biosafety-decisions-and-perceived-commercial-risks-The-role-of-GM-free-private-standards" title="Biosafety decisions and perceived commercial risks - The role of GM-free private standards" alt="link">Biosafety decisions and perceived commercial risks - The role of GM-free private standards</a></h2>

	
					<p>By Guillaume Gruère and Debdatta Sengupta, IFPRI, February 2009. As part of its IFPRI Discussion Papers series, the International Food Policy Research Institute has just published &quot;Biosafety decisions and perceived commercial risks: The role of GM-free private standards” by G. Gruere and D. Sengupta. The paper studies the interactions between importing food companies and their GM-free private standards and biotechnology decision making in developing countries.</p>
							<p><span class="date">24/03/2009</span></p>
	<div class="cnt">
	<a class="link" href="/en/Dossiers/S-T-Issues/Biotechnology/Relevant-publications/Biosafety-decisions-and-perceived-commercial-risks-The-role-of-GM-free-private-standards">Read more...</a>
</div>
